I you want to know the reason of this issue, read the following:
spark val is stored in here:
@transient lazy val spark: SparkSession = SparkSessionProvider._sparkSession

This constant is lazy and initialized with SparkSessionProvider._sparkSession, by default its value is null
@transient var _sparkSession: SparkSession = _

_sparkSession is initialized in method sqlBeforeAllTestCases:
override def beforeAll() {
    super.beforeAll()
    super.sqlBeforeAllTestCases()
  }

but method beforeAll is called after
implicit val sparkImpl: SparkSession = spark

Therefore this code get the value of lazy constant, which get the value of SparkSessionProvider._sparkSession, which is null in the moment this code executing

@jaysonsantos So are you saying the comment in the Django source code ("To achieve this in memcache backends, a negative timeout must be passed.") is wrong and we should open a ticket with Django?

I don't really understand your comment on changing it to `0xffffffe`. Wouldn't that make the value never expire? My understanding of the term "set-and-expire" (and the intention) is that it's the complete opposite!

